s, and the condensation of Bose-Einstein condensates\n  - Properties and characteristics\n    - High connectivity and entanglement between states\n      - Non-zero inner product between any two states\n      - Entanglement quantified by von Neumann entropy of the density matrix\n        - Density matrix as a generalization of the pure state description, allowing for the representation of mixed states and statistical ensembles\n        - Von Neumann entropy as a measure of the amount of entanglement and the degree of mixing in a quantum state\n        - Entanglement as a key resource for quantum information processing, enabling tasks such as teleportation, superdense coding, and quantum cryptography\n      - Vast information content inaccessible to local measurements\n        - Concept of quantum nonlocality and the violation of Bell's inequalities, demonstrating the existence of correlations that cannot be explained by classical theories\n        - Idea of quantum contextuality, where the outcome of a measurement depends on the context in which it is performed, leading to a holistic and non-reductionistic view of reality\n      - Contrasts with observed locality and separability of classical space due to decoherence\n        - Decoherence as a process of irreversible loss of coherence and entanglement due to the interaction between a quantum system and its environment\n        - Leads to the emergence of classical behavior and the suppression of quantum superpositions and interferences\n        - Explains the transition from the quantum to the classical world and the appearance of a objective, deterministic reality\n    - Emergence of three-dimensional space\n      - Interplay between measurement-induced symmetry breaking and morphic resonance-driven structure formation\n        - Observation and measurement collapse the wave function, breaking USMS symmetries and giving rise to classical structures and geometries\n          - Measurement as a non-unitary, irreversi